\begin_layout Subsection
Background
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea is the measure the economic performance.
 What are the perils of rapid development and lack of institutions - and
 how minor and seemingly immaterial steps can contribute to development.
 Hans Roesling has explained that social changes are slow to detect but
 can change dramatically.
 My background in finance enables me to assess the business feasibility
 and marketability of these ideas - and an interest in history allows me
 to delve into trends and historical time-series.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The specific interest I have is in the analysis of the spending pattern
 and its control by the societies.
 The control is to be measured as sensitivity to general trends across societies.
 Cultural notions are difficult to measure - but I believe that differences
 in sales figures of consumption goods can be a good indicator of basic
 trends.
 I do believe that classification of consumption articles (services or goods)
 - be done on lines of their need and purpose in the society (Research:
 phenomological needs of society).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the analysis of basic trends, I intend to see whether products and services
 (supply - cost of production) affects the demand (measured by sales)[RESEARCH]
 and whether advertisement revenues.
 The advertising elasticity and its relationship with the changing competition
 in the market is also to be explored.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Problem
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A key task is to test whether the short-term (seasonal) volatility of consumptio
n of goods correlates with the long-term sustenance.
 I suspect that goods that are have emotional (familial) values should vary
 differently from those that have a signalling affect in society.
 The consumption goods identified here are:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1.
 Signalling Products - ones that have indicated social mobility (the job
 here is to identify key components that have indiciated higher social status
 - due to historical/economic reasons).
 Availability of export products are evaluated on these grounds.
 Policy can help tune Veblen effects in its own interest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2.
 Consumption Goods - prices that vary driven by supply and demand and have
 no luxury or signalling factor.
 Food, commodities and utlilities are part of this group of products.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3.
 Services - the level of entrepreneurship - and social cohesion can make
 services accessible - but lack of them can be a burden (by addressing only
 demand rather than supply as is the case in India).
 Africa may not escape this trap if services don't improve and improving
 levels of income make services more approachable.
 Services could be further distinguished as those which affect the demand
 vs those that are driven by demand.
 It would be erroneous to assume that notions of nationality and the measures
 to keep markets local would assist purchasing power.
 The internal market and conventional wisdom of stronger economy implying
 faith in nationalized companies can also be explored in this area.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Luxury items, for instance haven't had a market in any of these areas -
 but there low consumption disqualifies them from this analysis.
 Only if the items are within a certain threshold level of the annual income
 of a certain population of individual.
 Luxury items - relative sales in a different market can explore opportunities
 for the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The demand curve analysis of ad-effects on revenue is also to be explored
 in this research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal is to delve into economic history to see - why certain patterns
 have prevailed (gold consumption in India, sports in the US) and what it
 implies to policy measures.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A further goal would be to think about sensitivity of these items to economic
 goals.
 My contention is that adjustment and sustenance of these consumption patterns
 should allow us to gauge the economic feasibility of growth.
 Analysis of countries like Burma can be improved in this regard.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For understanding of economic history, I find the comparison with settler
 societies as key to our understanding of the problems of developing world.
 The measure of cohesion in history and present can provide insights into
 reasons for economic issues as well as the future of the prevailing problems.
 However, this comparison is of minor concern to this research.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I am driven by seemingly disparate goals of serving the investment community
 and studying history to understand the stability of the patterns of response
 to economic conditions.
\end_layout

