The research wishes to revisit the corporate needs from a liquid-tradeable
 perspective and aspires to critique the models used for equity valuations
 and communication of risks in the industry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of the proposed research is to understand the relationship of volatilit
y and liquidity for equity valuations.
 More particularly - to find out if the industry betas are related to trends
 in volatility and liquidity and whether any standard indices can be a used
 as a proxy of the underlying economics.
 One can start with understanding the effect of foreign-exchange volatility
 on equity valuations.
 Note that volatility in this context, is more than the equivalent of risk
 in a CAPM framework.
 My research is not as much about fitting better models than it is to engage
 in economics that drive valuations and risk.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A side-task of this activity is to survey the sell-side research outputs
 and comment on the trend or influence of such research.
 Some preliminary work I have done in this area (blogged at ) inspects the
 assumptions on popular FCFF/WACC models and compares stochastic models
 (the Harrison Pliska no-aribtrage models based on tradeable assets).
 A similar backtesting exercise can help understand the effect of sell-side
 research on the market (in view of the exchange-rate and VIX fluctuations).
\end_layout

